<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-12-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-12-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="439" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d439">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">von Reichenau</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-12-19"><hi rend="italic">December 19,
                                        1896</hi></date>.</dateline>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 264.]</seg></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                                receipt of your note of the 12th instant, stating that the
                                Government of Germany would bear its share of the cost of safes for
                                the preservation of the records of the Samoan land commission and
                                that the consular representative at Apia had been so advised.</p>
                            <p>Adding that a copy of your note has been sent to Mr. Churchill, the
                                consul-general of this Government there, I beg to renew to you, sir,
                                etc.,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Richard
                                Olney.</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>